an exceptionally talented woman who achieved a degree of public influence to which not even her wealth and privilege would normally have entitled her. During the Revolution, when the lives of so many around her were destroyed, she succeeded in carving out a unique path for herself and making her views heard, first by the powerful men around her, later by the European public at large. Fontana provides the first in-depth look at her substantial output of writings on the theory and practice of the exercise of power, setting in sharp relief the dimension of Staël's life that she cared most about-politics. She was fascinated by the nature of public opinion, and believed that viable political regimes were founded on public trust and popular consensus. Fontana shows how Staël's ideas were shaped by the remarkable times in which she lived, and argues that it is only through a consideration of her political insights that we can fully understand Staël's legacy and its enduring relevance for us today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aAuthors, Frenchy18th centuryvBiography. 0aIntellectualszFrancevBiography. 0aWomen authors, Frenchy18th centuryvBiography. 0aWomen intellectualszFrancevBiography. 0aWomen political scientistszFrancevBiography. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066753008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400880614423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400880614.jpg  a978-3-11-063859-2  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016b2016  a978-3-11-066753-0  PUP eBook-Package 2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_S